Wash and dry all produce. Halve @grape tomatoes{4%ounce}. Trim and thinly slice
@scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Trim and quarter @button mushrooms{8%ounce}.
Mince or grate half the @garlic{2%clove}; halve remaining garlic crosswise.

Heat @butter{1%tablespoon} and a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%teaspoon} in a
#large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add mushrooms, @italian seasoning{2%teaspoon},
@salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until golden brown and tender,
~{6-8%minutes}. Reduce heat under pan to medium.

Add tomatoes, scallion whites, minced garlic, and another drizzle of
@olive oil{2%teaspoon} to pan. Cook, stirring often, until tomatoes are just
softened, ~{3-5%minutes}. Stir in half the @veggie stock concentrate{1} and
@water{1/4%cup}; bring to a simmer. Once simmering, remove pan from heat.

Meanwhile, halve @ciabatta bread{1} as if you were making a sandwich. Toast until
golden brown and crispy in a #toaster{} or under a #grill{}. Rub cut sides of
toasted bread with halved garlic cloves and drizzle with olive oil. Sprinkle with
remaining @italian seasoning{1%tablespoon} and season with salt and pepper. Halve
garlic bread on a diagonal to create triangles.

In a #medium pot{}, combine @water{2 1/2%cups}, remaining @veggie stock concentrate{1},
and @salt{1%tsp}. Bring to a boil. Once boiling, whisk in @cornmeal{1/2%cup}. Reduce
heat to low and cook, stirring often, until cornmeal is tender, ~{8-10%minutes}.

> TIP: If polenta gets too thick, whisk in hot water ½ cup at a time.

Heat pan with mushroom ragù over medium heat; stir in @butter{1%tablespoon}. Cook
until mixture is warmed through, ~{1-2%minutes}. Meanwhile, whisk @italian cheese blend{1/2%cup}
and @butter{2%tablespoon} into polenta until melted. Season generously with salt
and pepper. Divide polenta between #bowls{} and top with ragù. Sprinkle with
scallion greens. Serve with garlic bread on the side.